For something as important as authentication credentials you should put checks on both the client side *and* the server side. 

# Client side

I’m not an expert on JavaFX, but according to [this post](http://www.learningaboutelectronics.com/Articles/How-to-check-if-a-text-field-is-empty-in-JavaFX.php), you need to simply check the text contents of your data-entry fields. 

Here is my modified version of that code. I would use [`String#isBlank`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#isBlank()) rather than `isEmpty` to test for all whitespace in addition to testing for no text at all. 

```java
Label response = new Label();
Button submit = new Button( &quot;Submit&quot; );
TextField username = new TextField();
submit.setOnAction( action -&gt; 
    {
        if ( username.getText().isBlank() )
        {
            response.setText( &quot;The “User Name” field is required.&quot; );
        }
        else 
        {
            response.setText( &quot;The name you entered is &quot; + username.getText() );
            … 
        } 
    }
);
```


# Server side

On the database server, do as instructed in the correct [Answer by Eugenio](https://stackoverflow.com/a/70642827/642706). Set `NOT NULL` in columns that should never be empty. 

I would also add a trigger on those columns to verify incoming values are not empty/blank strings. (A NULL and a empty string are two different things.)

Simply put, from the java side you need to validate that your textfields and passwordfields aren&#39;t empty by using the isEmpty() method from the String class. Documentation can be found [HERE][1]


This method returns a boolean, and you can execute the rest of your code once data validation is done.

Oversimplified Example: 

    @FMXL fcnBtnSignUp(ActionEvent e) {
        // Check if the fields are empty, if they are, warn the user else continue

        if(txtFullName.getText().isEmpty() || txtGender.getText().isEmpty() || 
        txtEmail.getText().isEmpty() || txtPassword.getText().isEmpty() || 
        txtRePassword.getText().isEmpty()) {

        // Here you can set a send a popup to the user or have a label display &quot;All 
        fields must be filled to continue&quot;

        } else {

        // Now that you validated that none of the Strings you want to store in your 
         database are null, you can proceed. 

        // here goes your try/catch block and execute your ps statement.
        
        }
    }



Another thing, you should use passwordFields for passwords.. Documentation [HERE][2]


Lastly, think about using encryption if you are going to handle user credentials and store passwords in a database. BCrypt is a good library, documentation [HERE][3]


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#isEmpty()
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javafx/2/ui_controls/password-field.htm
  [3]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-security/site/docs/current/api/org/springframework/security/crypto/bcrypt/BCrypt.html

For the login method, it&#39;s the same thing.You validate that the fields aren&#39;t empty using the same method, then compare the entered Strings with what is stored in the database.

